SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS FOR RUNNING FP, FPIBE AND ASSOCIATED PROGRAMS


Items 02013, 02014, 06015 and 06016 should be consulted in detail
in order that FP, FPIBE and associated programs are utilised so that
the results they produce are properly interpreted.

The following should be adequate guidance on running the programs.

PC minimum specification

128 MB memory (RAM)
500MB hard disk space
Processor speed 1.5GHz or more recommended

It is recommended that all the programs, in particular the ‘MS-DOS’
batch programs DOMAPS and DOMAPC, are run in a sub-directory of the
C: drive of the PC, and not over any network. Attempting to run batch
programs over a network may lead to problems. 

GETTING STARTED

Copy all the files in the directory named FPV20 (on the CD)
to a working directory. It is not necessary to copy
sub-directories of FPV20, although they may be copied without
causing any problems.

Create a C:\ Command Prompt window (also known as a DOS box), and
create a working directory in which to carry out the work.
Copy all the files in the directory FPV20 to the working directory.

Make sure that all the files are copied from the directory FPV20 to
the working directory.

Within the working directory, execute FPCON by entering the command
FPCON.EXE (or FPCON). The first line returned to the screen should
state that the version of FPCON has the revision date May 2006.

Enter responses at the prompts. Those corresponding to
the first example in Item 02014 (on page 38) should be
used to start with. If an error is made in the course of entering
the responses, the program should be terminated by entering CTRL-C,
and run again. 

Once FPCON has been successfully run, files named GEO.DAT, MAP.DAT,
FLOW.DAT, GEOSUP.DAT and RESPIN.DAT will have been produced. Check
that these files have been created and are in the working directory.

Once the files are present, enter the command FP.EXE (or FP),
to run the program FP, or enter the command FPIBE.EXE (or FPIBE) to
run the program FPIBE. It is recommended that FPIBE be run in preference
to FP, for reasons given in Item 06015. The input files required for FP and
FPIBE are identical. (The vast majority of the instructions in the two programs, FP and FPIBE, are identical, and all the information on running FP applies equally to FPIBE.)

FP or FPIBE should then run and produce output files that conform to the
results in Figures 1, 2 and 3 of Item 02014.

Note that output files intended for use with EASYPLOT have to
be edited if they are to be used with other graph plotting
programs. This may be a particularly important consideration 
if the isobar plots are to be produced. 

The output filenames produced by FPIBE differ from those of FP
by starting with the letter B.

Consequently if the isobar plots are required and FPIBE has been run, 
it is necessary to copy the file bcp3d.dat to cp3d.dat before running 
the program CONTOUR, simply because CONTOUR has been written to read 
data from the file cp3d.dat output from FP, rather than the corresponding
file output from FPIBE, which is named bcp3d.dat. (MS-DOS commands are
not case-sensitive.)  
         
CARRYING ON

To investigate a case of interest, consider whether the wing is
a simple swept and tapered wing or a wing with a single crank. If it
is one of these types then FPCON should be of use directly,
provided the body (if any) may be represented by a cylinder.

Prior to running either of the batch programs, DOMAPS or DOMAPC,
carefully consult Sections 7.2.2 and 7.4.2 regarding their use.

To represent a shaped body, Section 8.5 of Item 02014 
should be consulted.

If the wing has more than one crank, or has a curved leading
edge and/or trailing edge, refer to Section 9 of
Item 02014.

Once input files for FP or FPIBE have been produced, it is prudent,
before running FP or FPIBE, to check that the geometry specified
by the geometry file is the one required. To do this, run
MAPONLY and GRIDPROC as indicated in Appendix B of 
Item 02014, and examine the results as suggested
there.

If an FP or FPIBE run diverges, or gives irregular results, try 
running a case with low Mach number and low incidence
to see if the problem is associated mainly with the geometry,
or with the flow case.

Refer to Section 10 of Item 02014 for suggestions on 
how to proceed if FP or FPIBE fails or presents problems.

Generally, it is recommended that FP and FPIBE are run to convergence.
This usually entails runs of several thousand iterations, most of these
being with the fine grid utilised (see, for example, Figure 2 of
Item 06016.)

